{"title_page": "Joe Biden sexual assault allegation", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Redirect|Tara Reade|the actress|Tara Reid}}\n{{mergeto|2017\u201318 United States political sexual scandals|discuss=Talk:Joe Biden sexual assault allegation#Merger proposal|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Allegation made by Tara Reade in March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Joe Biden, official photo.jpg\n| width1 = 147\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = SenareaidIDTaraReade.webp\n| width2 = 150\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = Biden (left) and Reade (right)\n}}\nIn April 2019, former Senate staff assistant Tara Reade alleged that Senator [[Joe Biden]] sexually assaulted her in a [[Capitol Hill]] office building in 1993. Her March 2020 retelling garnered a response from his spokesperson, denying the allegation. Three people later said she told them of his assault between 1993 and 2008. An August 1993 anonymous caller (whom Reade identified as her mother in 2020) on ''[[Larry King Live]]'' said her daughter had unpublicized problems with a prominent senator.\n\n== Background ==\n=== Tara Reade ===\nAt age twenty-nine, Tara Reade was a staff assistant in the office of then Senator Joe Biden from December 1992 to August 1993 with responsibilities such as supervision of the office's [[page of the United States Senate|intern]]s and [[internal mail|mail delivery]].<ref name=\"Halper_3/31/2020\">{{cite news|last=Halper|first=Katie|url=https://www.currentaffairs.org/2020/03/tara-reade-tells-her-story|title=Tara Reade Tells Her Story|date=March 31, 2020|magazine=[[Current Affairs (magazine)|Current Affairs]]|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlso known as Alexandra Tara Reade,<ref name=\"girl walks\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theunion.com/opinion/columns/alexandra-tara-reade-a-girl-walks-into-the-senate/ |date=April 18, 2020 |title=Alexandra Tara Reade: A girl walks into the Senate|last=Reade|first=Alexandra Tara|website=www.theunion.com|language=en-US|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2020/03/31/a-woman-accuses-joe-biden-of-sexual-assault-and-all-hell-breaks-loose-online-heres-what-we-know/|title=A woman accuses Joe Biden of sexual assault, and all hell breaks loose online. Here's what we know|last=Marcotte|first=Amanda|date=March 31, 2020|website=Salon|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> she is a writer<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2020/04/17/joe-biden-tara-reade-metoo-problem-sexual-assault-allegation-column/5140707002/ |date=April 17, 2020 |title=If Joe Biden wants due process in his sexual assault case, he should back it for others|first=Cathy|last=Young|website=USA TODAY}}</ref> from [[Nevada County, California]],<ref name=\"girl walks\"/> who helps run [[non-profit organization]]s.<ref name=\"Halper_3/31/2020\"/><ref name=\"WE200415\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alexandrareade.com/|title=Alexandra Tara Reade - Home|date=April 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404045216/https://www.alexandrareade.com/|archive-date=April 4, 2019}}</ref>  She earned a law degree from [[Seattle University School of Law]] but has not practiced law.<ref name=\"Halper_3/31/2020\" /><ref name=\"WE200415\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/everything-we-know-about-the-biden-sexual-assault-allegation|title=Everything we know about the Biden sexual assault allegation|last1=Larsen|first1=Emily|date=April 15, 2020|publisher=Washington Examiner|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> She stated that she is an [[expert witness]] for [[Monterey County, California]] in [[domestic violence]] cases, work for which she receives a stipend.<ref name=\"WE200415\" /><ref name=\"Halper_3/31/2020\"/><ref name=\"WE200415\" />  She has a daughter.<ref name=\"Halper_3/31/2020\"/>\n\n=== Joe Biden ===\n{{Main|Joe Biden}}\nJoe Biden was a U.S. senator from Delaware from 1973 to 2009, and Vice President of the U.S. from 2009 to 2017. {{As of|April 2020}}, he is the presumptive [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]] nominee in the [[2020 United States presidential election]].\n\n== Allegations ==\n\n=== Reade's prior reports and contact with media ===\nIn April 2019, Reade contacted a reporter and alleged that Biden touched her inappropriately while she worked in his U.S. Senate office. Reade made the allegation after watching an episode of the ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'' on April 1, 2019, in which Nevada politician [[Lucy Flores]] had alleged that Biden sniffed her hair and kissed the back of her head shortly before a political rally in 2014.<ref name=InterceptTimesup>{{cite news|url=https://theintercept.com/2020/03/24/joe-biden-metoo-times-up/|first=Ryan|last=Grim|title=Time's Up Said It Could Not Fund a #MeToo Allegation Against Joe Biden, Citing Its Nonprofit Status and His Presidential Run|website=[[The Intercept]]|date=March 24, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Nevada County woman\">{{Cite news|first=Alan|last=Riquelmy|title=Nevada County woman says Joe Biden inappropriately touched her while working in his U.S. Senate office|newspaper=[[The Union (newspaper)|The Union]]|date=April 3, 2019|url=https://www.theunion.com/news/nevada-county-woman-says-joe-biden-inappropriately-touched-her-while-working-in-his-u-s-senate-office/ |access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref> She further stated that she believed she was fired from Biden's office because she had refused to serve drinks at an event, and that she believed being fired from Biden's office had ruined her career in Washington, D.C.<ref name=\"Nevada County woman\"/>\n\n''[[The Union (newspaper)|The Union]]'', a local newspaper in [[Grass Valley, California]], published an essay by Reade on April 17, 2019, in which she described her encounter with Biden and wrote: \"...this is not a story about sexual misconduct; it is a story about abuse of power.\"  Reade goes on to write, \"Senator Biden would touch me on the shoulder or hold his hand on my shoulder running his index finger up my neck during a meeting \u2026 What started with promise and possibility, ended because some prominent Senator decided that he liked my legs and objectified me.\"<ref name=\"girl walks\"/>\n\nIn January&ndash;February 2020, Reade sought help regarding the elements of her allegations from [[Time's Up Legal Defense Fund]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/biden-campaign-team-denies-past-sexual-assault-allegation-former-senate-staffer-1494794|title=Joe Biden's sexual assault accuser wants to be able to speak out without fear of \"powerful men\"|first=Chantal|last=Da Silva|date=March 27, 2020|website=Newsweek}}</ref> The Fund ultimately declined to assist Reade, having determined that as a [[non-profit organization|non-profit]] it is legally constrained from doing so because of Internal Revenue Service restrictions that pertain to candidates running for election.<ref name=InterceptTimesup/><ref name=\"PoliticoHolly\"/>\n\n=== Reade's account ===\nIn March 2020, Reade alleged that Biden had pushed her against a wall and penetrated her with his fingers in a Capitol Hill office building in 1993.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  Reade made the allegation in an interview with [[Katie Halper]] which was released as a podcast on March 25, 2020.  Reade later told [[NPR]], \"His hands went underneath my clothing and he was touching me in my private areas and without my consent.\" She said that when she pulled away, Biden looked puzzled and said, \"Come on, man, I heard you liked me,\" then told her that \"You're nothing to me, nothing.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAddressing what her objective was for making her allegation public, Reade said during the interview, \"I'm hoping by coming forward with this\u2014and I know it's hard to listen to, and it's hard to live in it, right? But my justice now, the only justice I can have, is to be moving freely in the world and to heal and not be silenced.\"<ref name=\"Halper_3/31/2020\" /> On April 9, 2020, she filed a police report with the [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia|Washington Metropolitan Police Department]] alleging she was sexually assaulted in spring 1993.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Vitali|first1=Ali|last2=Memoli|first2=Mike|title=Woman broadens claims against Biden to include sexual assault|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/woman-broadens-claims-against-biden-include-sexual-assault-n1182296 |access-date=April 16, 2020|work=NBC News|date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> NPR confirmed that a record of the police report named Biden.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |last1=Khalid |first1=Asma |title=On The Record: A Former Biden Staffer's Sexual Assault Allegation |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/04/19/837966525/on-the-record-a-former-biden-staffers-sexual-assault-allegation |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |work=NPR |date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Reade acknowledged that the statute of limitations has lapsed, and she stated that she filed the report \"for safety reasons only.\"<ref name=\"nyt\">{{Cite news |last=Lerer |first=Lisa |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/joe-biden-tara-reade-sexual-assault-complaint.html |title=Examining Tara Reade's Sexual Assault Allegation Against Joe Biden |date=April 12, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=April 12, 2020 |last2=Ember |first2=Sydney}}</ref><ref name=\"Mangan-200414\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/14/joe-biden-accused-of-sex-assault-amid-challenge-to-donald-trump.html|title=Joe Biden is accused of sexual assault as he heads toward election fight with Trump|work=[[CNBC]]|date=April 14, 2020 | access-date=April 15, 2020|first=Dan|last=Mangan}}</ref>  According to Reade, she did not share her full allegation when she initially came forward in 2019 because, in part, she \"just didn't have the courage\",<ref name=\"PoliticoHolly\">{{cite web |last1=Otterbein |first1=Holly |title=Biden sexual assault allegation roils #MeToo movement |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/23/tara-reade-biden-202785 |website=Politico}}</ref> and that after publicly alleging in 2019 that Biden had touched her inappropriately, she said she received death threats and a \"wave of criticism\"<ref name=\"nyt\" /> and was [[doxed]].<ref name=\"Slate\">{{cite web |last1=Cauterucci |first1=Christina |title=Joe Biden Sails Under the New York Times' Bar for Sexual Abuse |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/joe-biden-harassment-nytimes.html |website=Slate |accessdate=26 April 2020}}</ref> On April 27, 2020, ''Business Insider'' reported that Reade's former neighbor Lynda LaCasse said that Reade told her about the alleged assault in 1995 or 1996, saying that \"This happened, and I know it did because I remember talking about it.\" In the article, LaCasse did not mention Biden by name but did say, \u201cI remember her saying, here was this person that she was working for and she idolized him,\" <ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/former-neighbor-corroborates-joe-bidens-accuser-2020-4|title=A former neighbor of Joe Biden's accuser Tara Reade has come forward to corroborate her sexual assault account, saying Reade discussed the allegations in detail in the mid-1990s|last=McHugh|first=Rich|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Biden response ===\n\nBiden's campaign representatives have denied the allegations. His deputy campaign manager stated, \"Vice President Biden has dedicated his public life to changing the culture and the laws around violence against women. He authored and fought for the passage and reauthorization of the landmark Violence Against Women Act. He firmly believes that women have a right to be heard \u2014 and heard respectfully. Such claims should also be diligently reviewed by an independent press. What is clear about this claim: It is untrue. This absolutely did not happen.\"<ref name=\"nyt\"/>\n\n=== ''The New York Times''{{'}} investigative reporting ===\nOn April 12, 2020, ''The New York Times'' released an analysis of their investigative reporting in which they interviewed Reade, several of her friends, lawyers, nearly two dozen people who worked with Biden in the early 1990s, and seven women who accused Biden of kissing, hugging, or touching them in ways that had made them feel uncomfortable. They stated that they found no other allegations of sexual assault in the course of their reporting. Several of the seven women said that they believed Reade but had no new knowledge about the incident.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Two friends of Reade confirmed to ''The New York Times'' that she had told them of the alleged assault (one in 1993 shortly after the alleged assault took place, the other in 2008). Reade's brother has also publicly stated that she had told him about it,<ref name=\"nyt\" /> initially saying that Reade told him that Biden had touched her neck and shoulders, but several days later he told ''The Washington Post'' that he also remembered that she had said that Biden had reached \"under her clothes.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ruth|first1=Marcus |date=April 15, 2020 |title=Assessing Tara Reade's allegations|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/04/15/seriousness-flaws-tara-reades-allegations/|website=The Washington Post |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Biden's Senate Chief of Staff and Deputy Chief of Staff during 1992-1993 and the office's long-term executive assistant expressed doubts as to the veracity of Reade's account, stating that they would have recalled Reade's complaints about Biden's conduct had she made them.  They also said that the alleged behavior would have been out of character for Biden. Melissa Lefko, another staff assistant for Biden during that time period, told the reporters that she had never experienced harassment and that in her opinion, Biden's office was a \"very supportive environment for women.\"<ref name=\"nyt\" />\n\nReade said she reported sexual harassment to her supervisors in Biden's office at the time, but her recollection of to whom has shifted and none of her former supervisors recall any such event.<ref name=Walsh-200415/> Reade's former colleague Lorraine Sanchez also said that Reade told her in 1995 or 1996 that Reade had been sexually harassed \"by her former boss in Washington, DC.\" Sanchez said she does not recall if Reade offered details about the sort of harassment she allegedly suffered, or if she named Biden.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== ''Larry King Live'' phone call ===\nOn April 24, 2020, an unidentified source who heard Katie Halper's interview with ''[[The Intercept]]''{{'}}s [[Ryan Grim]] sent Grim a video of an August 11, 1993, phone call to ''[[Larry King Live]]'' in which a woman asks: \"I'm wondering what a staffer might do besides go to the press in Washington. My daughter has just left there after working for a prominent senator and could not get through with her problems at all. The only thing she could have done was go to the press, and she chose not to do it out of respect for him.\"<ref name=Grim>{{cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2020/04/24/new-evidence-tara-reade-joe-biden/|title=New Evidence Supporting Credibility of Tara Reade's Allegation Against Joe Biden Emerges|last=Grim|first=Ryan|date=April 24, 2020|website=The Intercept|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=Kalmbacher>{{cite web|url=https://lawandcrime.com/2020-election/new-evidence-appears-to-corroborate-tara-reades-sexual-assault-claim-against-joe-biden-video/|title=New Evidence Appears to Corroborate Tara Reade's Sexual Assault Claim Against Joe Biden (VIDEO)|last=Kalmbacher|first=Colin|date=|website=Law&Crime|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200425185455/https://lawandcrime.com/2020-election/new-evidence-appears-to-corroborate-tara-reades-sexual-assault-claim-against-joe-biden-video/|archive-date=April 25, 2020|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> Reade told ''The Intercept'' that it was her mother's voice on the call.<ref name=Grim />\n\n== Media coverage ==\n[[Joan Walsh]], writing in ''[[The Nation]]'', said that Reade's \"allegation against Biden doesn't stand up to close scrutiny\".<ref name=Walsh-200415>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/politics/tara-reade-joe-biden-democrats/|title=The Troublesome Tara Reade Story|work=[[The Nation]]|date=April 15, 2020 | access-date=April 16, 2020|first=Joan|last=Walsh}}</ref> On March 28, 2020, ''The Guardian'' columnist Arwa Mahdawi wrote an op-ed: \"Why has the media ignored sexual assault allegations against Biden?\" She expressed that it is frustrating to see conservatives \"weaponize the accusations against Biden\" and \"to see so many liberals turning a blind eye\" to Reade's allegation.<ref name=\"TheWeek-200416\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theweek.co.uk/106651/joe-biden-the-sexual-assault-claim-dividing-democrats|title=Joe Biden: the sexual assault claim dividing Democrats|date=April 16, 2020|work=[[The Week]]|access-date=April 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Mahdawi-200328>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/28/joe-biden-sexual-assault-allegations-why-has-media-ignored-claims|title=Why has the media ignored sexual assault and misbehaviour allegations against Biden?|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=March 28, 2020 | access-date=April 16, 2020|first=Arwa|last=Mahdawi}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' was criticized by several commentators who asserted that they had delayed coverage of the allegation and argued their coverage differed from reporting on other allegations in the past.<ref name=floodgates>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/04/media-floodgates-open-joe-biden-tara-reade-allegation|title=The Media Floodgates Finally Open on Biden Sexual Assault Allegation|last=Ecarma|first=Caleb|date=April 14, 2020|website=Vanity Fair|url-status=live|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Its executive editor, [[Dean Baquet]], published an [[op-ed]] on April 13, 2020, responding to these criticisms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/04/the-new-york-times-denies-tara-reade-the-christine-blasey-ford-treatment/|title=The New York Times Denies Tara Reade the Christine Blasey Ford Treatment|date=April 14, 2020|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Slate\"/><ref name=floodgates/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/13/business/media/joe-biden-tara-reade-new-york-times.html|title=The Times Took 19 Days to Report an Accusation Against Biden. Here's Why.|date=April 13, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Baquet responded to a controversy about a line in the news story that was removed after the piece's initial publication. The sentence previously read: \"The Times found no pattern of sexual misconduct by Mr. Biden, beyond the hugs, kisses and touching that women previously said made them uncomfortable.\" Baquet explained that it had been included originally in order not to falsely imply that other individuals had made allegations as invasive in nature as Reade's, but was thereafter removed because of \"awkward phrasing issue that could be read different ways.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/492680-ny-times-faces-blowback-for-removal-of-controversial-passage-on-biden-sexual|title=NY Times faces blowback for removal of controversial passage on Biden sexual assault allegation|last=Swanson|first=Ian|date=April 14, 2020|website=The Hill|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> Baquet stated that the edit was made after [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|the Biden campaign]] had objected to it because \"[it] made it look like there were other instances in which he had been accused of sexual misconduct.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n;Multimedia\n*{{cite web|first=Katie|last=Halper|authorlink=|title=Biden accuser: \"I wanted to be a senator; I didn't want to sleep with one\" (audio)|website=Katie Halper podcast|date=March 30, 2020|url=https://soundcloud.com/katie-halper/tara-to-post|access-date=}}\n*{{cite news|author = [[Krystal Ball]]|series = Rising|url = https://thehill.com/hilltv/rising/489719-tara-reade-discusses-biden-allegation-with-hilltvs-rising|type = video interview|title = Tara Reade discusses Biden allegation with Hill.TV's 'Rising'|newspaper = [[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date = March 26, 2020}}\n*{{cite AV media|url = https://larrykinglive.blogs.cnn.com/|archive-url = https://www.mrctv.org/videos/video-joe-bidens-accusers-mother-talking-cnn-1993|publisher = CNN|series = [[Larry King Live]]|archive-date = April 24, 2020|date = August 11, 1993|author = [[Larry King]]|title = Washington: The Cruelest City on Earth?|type = video which includes a [[call in show|call]] from a San Luis Obispo, California, woman about daughter's departure from job working for an unnamed U.S. Senator}}  \n\n{{Joe Biden}}\n\n[[Category:2020 controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|Assault allegation]]\n[[Category:Mass media-related controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sexual assaults in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sexual misconduct allegations]]\n[[Category:Political sex scandals in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Redirect|Tara Reade|the actress|Tara Reid}}\n{{mergeto|2017\u201318 United States political sexual scandals|discuss=Talk:Joe Biden sexual assault allegation#Merger proposal|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Allegation made by Tara Reade in March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date